{{Nihongo|'''Minamoto no Sanetomo'''|源 実朝||September 12, 1192 – February 13, 1219, r. 1203–1219}} was the third ''{{ill|Shogun|en|Shogun|qid=Q131767|lt=Shogun|1=Shogun}}'' of the {{ill|Kamakura shogunate|en|Kamakura shogunate|qid=Q736839|lt=Kamakura shogunate|1=Kamakura shogunate}}. He was the second son of the Kamakura shogunate founder, [[Minamoto no Yoritomo]]. His mother was {{ill|Hōjō Masako|en|Hōjō Masako|qid=Q463961|lt=Hōjō Masako|1=Hōjō Masako}} and his older brother was the second Kamakura shogun [[Minamoto no Yoriie]].

His childhood name was {{nihongo|'''Senman'''|千万}}. He was the last head of the [[Minamoto clan]] of {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. His {{ill|Dharma name|en|Dharma name|qid=Q1543672|lt=Dharma name|1=Dharma name}} was {{nihongo|'''Daijijiden seini'i goshoko jingi'''|大慈寺殿正二位丞相公神儀}}.

He was an accomplished ''{{ill|Waka (poetry)|en|Waka (poetry)|qid=Q737148|lt=waka|1=Waka (poetry)}}'' poet.

== Early life ==
[[File:Minamoto no Sanetomo.jpg|thumb|220px|Sanetomo in court clothing, painting by the priest Goshin.]]
{{more citations needed|section|date=March 2018}}
After the death of Yoritomo in 1199, Sanetomo's maternal grandfather {{ill|Hōjō Tokimasa|en|Hōjō Tokimasa|qid=Q589811|lt=Hōjō Tokimasa|1=Hōjō Tokimasa}} usurped the political and military power of the Shogunate, relegating the position and title of ''[[:en:Sei-i Taishōgun|Sei-i Taishōgun]]'', or ''shōgun'', to a figurehead. Through hereditary succession, Sanetomo's older brother Yoriie became ''Sei-i Taishōgun'' in 1202, only to be stripped of the title a year later and put under house arrest for plotting against the {{ill|Hōjō clan|en|Hōjō clan|qid=Q834364|lt=Hōjō clan|1=Hōjō clan}}.{{Citation needed|date= November 2011}} This was presumably to keep the ''shōgun'' a child and thus needing a regent (''shikken'') to make decisions in his place. Shortly thereafter, in 1203, Sanetomo became head of the Minamoto clan and was appointed ''Sei-i Taishōgun''.

A year later, Yoriie was assassinated by the Hōjō. Sanetomo was never more than a puppet for his mother {{ill|Hōjō Masako|en|Hōjō Masako|qid=Q463961|lt=Hōjō Masako|1=Hōjō Masako}} and maternal uncle Hōjō Yoshitoki, who used him as a pawn in their war with their father Tokimasa; Tokimasa tried to depose his grandson a number of times, beginning in 1205, causing Sanetomo to fear for his life thereafter.{{Citation needed|date= November 2011}}

=== ''Waka'' poet ===
Sanetomo, understanding his own powerlessness and not wanting to meet the same fate as his elder brother, put his time and energy into writing {{ill|Waka (poetry)|en|Waka (poetry)|qid=Q737148|lt=waka poetry|1=Waka (poetry)}} and gaining posts within the powerless but honorary imperial court. Sanetomo was a talented poet, writing over 700 poems between the age 17 and 22 while he was tutored by {{ill|Fujiwara no Teika|en|Fujiwara no Teika|qid=Q378425|lt=Fujiwara no Teika|1=Fujiwara no Teika}}{{Citation needed|date= November 2011}}. He published his private waka collection ''Kinkai Wakashū'', even having one of his [[waka (poetry)#Tanka|tanka]] included in the anthology ''Ogura [[:en:Hyakunin Isshu|Hyakunin Isshu]]'' ("100 Poems by 100 Poets"), a collection of Japanese poems of the {{ill|Heian period|en|Heian period|qid=Q193292|lt=Heian|1=Heian period}} and early Kamakura periods. Sanetomo reached the third-highest post of the imperial court, ''[[:en:Udaijin|Udaijin]]'' (Minister of the Right or "vice-premier") in 1218.<ref name="nussbaum633">Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "Minamoto no Sanetomo" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', pp. 633–634|page=633}}</ref>

Eventually, Sanetomo lapsed into inactivity and despair, plagued by fear of assassination and tormented by his chronic {{ill|alcoholism|en|alcoholism|qid=Q15326|lt=alcoholism|1=Alcoholism}} (an addiction which Priest {{ill|Eisai|en|Eisai|qid=Q366128|lt=Eisai|1=Eisai}} once tried to break by replacing alcohol with {{ill|Tea|en|Tea|qid=Q6097|lt=Tea|1=Tea}}).{{Citation needed|date= November 2011}}

=== Death ===
[[File:Tsurugaoka.jpg|thumb|Grand stairway at [[Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|Tsurugaoka Hachiman-gū]] in Kamakura – the scene of Sanetomo's assassination]]
[[File:KamakuraHachimanguTree.jpg|thumb|Shinto symbolism encompasses the girth of the ancient ginkgo tree at the foot of the stairs leading to the upper level of Kamakura's great Hachiman Shrine. The tree, near the spot where Sanetomo was ambushed and killed, was blown down on 10 March 2010.]]
[[File:Minamoto-no-Sanetomo's-cenotaph.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Cenotaph|en|Cenotaph|qid=Q321053|lt=Cenotaph|1=Cenotaph}} honoring Sanetomo in Kamakura's {{ill|Jufuku-ji|en|Jufuku-ji|qid=Q167087|lt=Jufuku-ji|1=Jufuku-ji}}'s cemetery]]

Under heavy snow on the evening of February 13, 1219 (''{{ill|Jōkyū|en|Jōkyū|qid=Q1195428|lt=Jōkyū|1=Jōkyū}} 1, 27th day of the 1st month''), Sanetomo was coming down from the Senior Shrine at [[Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|Tsurugaoka Hachiman-gū]] after participating in a ceremony celebrating his nomination to [[:en:Udaijin|Udaijin]].<ref name="AK"/> His nephew and son of deposed Yoriie, [[:en:Kugyō (Minamoto no Yoshinari)|Kugyō]], came out from beside the stone stairway of the shrine and assassinated him.<ref name="AK">Azuma Kagami; Mutsu (1995/06: 102-104)</ref> For his act, he was himself beheaded a few hours later,<ref name="AK"/> thus bringing the {{ill|Seiwa Genji|en|Seiwa Genji|qid=Q2164991|lt=Seiwa Genji|1=Seiwa Genji}} line of the Minamoto clan and their rule in Kamakura to a sudden end.

Minamoto no Sanetomo was succeeded by {{ill|Kujō Yoritsune|en|Kujō Yoritsune|qid=Q471780|lt=Kujō Yoritsune|1=Kujō Yoritsune}}, son-in-law of Yoriie, as fourth ''shōgun'' of the Kamakura shogunate.

